                        <div class="markdown">
                            <span class="preserve-whitespace">Penelope left after one last long look at Laika. Anxiety lept back into her throat in jolts, every two steps. Hope and fear was reminded with every sound. 

Should she bring the chair like she promised? Would that just prolong his upset? She decided to wheel a chair to the outside of his room so Enzan wouldn&#39;t have to look at it. Then she came back in. 

&quot;What took so long?&quot; Enzan said. &quot;Where&#39;s the chair?&quot;

&quot;I. Ran into Izabella. She said you need to wait. Four hours. They&#39;re taking him off the ventilator and no one else should come until it&#39;s over.&quot; Pen sputtered out the poorly rehearsed words she&#39;d come up with in the hallway and felt them fall flat. Enzan looked away from her. 

&quot;I have to be there,&quot; Enzan said firmly. &quot;Izabella shouldn&#39;t be alone with him.&quot; 

&quot;Enzan, he&#39;s strapped down. She&#39;s safe. He&#39;s safe. You need to rest.&quot; Penelope sat down beside him. He glared at her with all the malice he had left. 

But it wasn&#39;t much. He laid back down. Everything ached. 

&quot;Blues. Set a timer for four hours from now. Penelope. You&#39;d damn well better distract me enough to wait.&quot; 

Pen nodded, brushing her hair from her face. &quot;Yeah... I&#39;ll read to you until then, okay?&quot; 

Enzan didn&#39;t respond, but closed his eyes. Under Penelope&#39;s words, he eventually calmed enough to at least wait. Pen waited for a message from Searchman, and bidded Blues to hold off on his timer.</span>

