            <div class="chatlog__message " data-message-id="734735459422306334" id="message-734735459422306334" title="Message sent: 20-Jul-20 07:36 AM">
                    <div class="chatlog__content">
                        <div class="markdown">
                            <span class="preserve-whitespace">The day dragged on, though the concept was lost to the person in ICU. Laika saw the world in hazy vingettes. People and things were merely blotches of color moving about the blur of space he could see. Every time his eyes closed, the scene would be different. 

One color was a constant beyond the others, a mint. It stayed close despite his fading in and out, providing another sensation: touch. Laika could feel warmth in his hand, and it was good. Even if it faded to blue and white and discomfort, the touch came back. Soft, warm, soothing. 

During one fade, Laika&#39;s ventilator was removed. An oxygen mask replaced it, to ensure he was taking enough of the element in. He woke up again to find the mint color more refined: a familiar woman. She looked at him in a way he couldn&#39;t describe, speaking soft nonsense. She came in close enough to cover his sight. With blindness, a soft touch pressed to his head. It was nice. 

Then she left, and the lights went dim. Laika looked around where he could, finding no one. His heart rate went up a tick before the medicines brought him back to calm. He was alone.

His sight finally got to the point where he could see the far wall clearly. The nurse&#39;s communication board was chocked full of scrawled notes too complex for him to decipher. He could finally understand someone soon after that, a nurse who had come in to check vitals. They didn&#39;t say much besides hello, but hello was enough. The world was getting clearer, but because of that, he failed to rest. Laika stared up at the ceiling long after the last nurse left, trying to piece things together.</span>

